Exciting News for Eclipse Explorer's Carnival Participants!

Hey there, fellow cosmic enthusiasts!
The countdown to the Eclipse Explorer's Carnival is on, and we can hardly contain our excitement!

We know you've been eagerly preparing for all the amazing events we have in store, and the time has finally come for you to start sharing your stellar creations!

Eclipse Art Showcase - Show us your out-of-this-world artistic talents and send us your creative arts!

Virtual Sci-Fi Storytelling - Unleash your imagination through storytelling in the cosmos, Send us your story!

Quiz Competition - Prove your cosmic knowledge and win fabulous prizes! (Quiz Competition on 30th September)

Eclipse Poetry Slam - Let your words take flight in the universe.
Send us your eclipse poetry!

Who Can Explain Eclipse Better! - Share your insights and amaze us with your eclipse wisdom. Explain what eclipse is in the most innovative way possible and win prizes!

Eclipse Crafts - Craft your way through the galaxies! Craft whatever you want but it must be related to eclipse (example: Eclipse Glasses)

Eclipse Scrapbook - Create a cosmic memory album that's truly otherworldly. Make an eclipse scrapbook and show us and your friends!

It's time to submit your registration form for these incredible events!

Registration form for 'Eclipse Explorer's Carnival' : https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSf0nYXM_ino9y487E_F8j0sIXZ_Mc5zoKYh_oTwk1CK0SrDVQ/viewform?usp=sf_link

Fill-up this form for submission guidelines!

Don't miss your chance to shine like a supernova and be a part of this cosmic celebration. Send us your works, and let's make this carnival unforgettable!

Remember to check our official 'Discover The Eclipse Thrills ' page daily for submission guidelines and deadlines. We can't wait to see what you've got in store for us!

Let's make this carnival a journey to remember, together!

Rare Triple eclipse on Jupiter
NASA's Hubble Space Telescope captured an image of Jupiter with five spots on its upper half. These spots are actually created by the alignment of three of Jupiter's largest moons: Io, Ganymede, and Callisto. The spots are their shadows. Io's shadow is slightly above and to the left of the center, Ganymede's is on the left edge of Jupiter, and Callisto's is near the right edge. Discover
Rare Triple eclipse on Jupiter NASA's Hubble Space Telescope captured an image of Jupiter with five spots on its upper half. These spots are actually created by the alignment of three of Jupiter's largest moons: Io, Ganymede, and Callisto. The spots are their shadows. Io's shadow is slightly above and to the left of the center, Ganymede's is on the left edge of Jupiter, and Callisto's is near the right edge. In the image, you can only see two of the moons: Io as a white circle in the center and Ganymede as a blue circle on the upper right. Callisto is not visible in this picture. This image was taken on March 28, 2004, using Hubble's Near Infrared Camera and Multi-Object Spectrometer.
